text = "	The robin is a bird [color=peru]R[/color] such that for any birds [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color], [color=orange]y[/color] and [color=orangered]z[/color], the following condition hods:

[center](([b][color=green]R[/color][/b] [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color]) [color=orange]y[/color]) [color=orangered]z[/color] = ([color=orange]y[/color] [color=orangered]z[/color]) [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color][/center]

	It is similar to the cardinal, both \"rearrange\" the birds [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color], [color=orange]y[/color] and [color=orangered]z[/color], this can be very useful when finding new birds. In the following levels you will explore some ways this bird can be used.

	The amount of parenthesis in some of these rules can be confusing, to avoid this problem there is a convention that ([color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color] [color=orange]y[/color]) [color=orangered]z[/color] can be simply written as [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color] [color=orange]y[/color] [color=orangered]z[/color]. On the other hand, [color=darkgoldenrod]x[/color] ([color=orange]y[/color] [color=orangered]z[/color]) stays the same. This way the lack of parenthesis is not ambiguous anymore, if there are"
